modes of cross-cultural engagement offer new foundations for the enterprise of learning from cultural others. Each chapter works from Chinese perspectives to theorize the location of knowledge, its conditions of production, and the modes through which its content or adequacy is legitimated, challenged, and sustained. Rather than reproducing Eurocentric knowledge production in Chinese form, the mobilization of Chinese thought as a generally applicable body of theory actually breaks down clear boundaries between Chinese and non-Chinese thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aGlobalization. 0aHumanities. 0aPhilosophy, Chinese. 0aSocial sciences. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aHistory : History. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Philosophy. 4aSociology : Social Theory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Epistemology.2bisacsh1 aBrown, Miranda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheek, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Gloria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDowdle, Michael W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGungwu, Wang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJenco, Leigh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJenco, Leigh, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLi, Chenyang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNakajima, Takahiro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVillagran, Ignacio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWu, Guanjun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of